WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:27.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.800
[Amit Varma]: great dilemmas of politics is the question of when a politician finally comes to power,

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:36.360
[Amit Varma]: does his focus shift to governance, or does it stay with politics? Does he try to do a

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:41.560
[Amit Varma]: good job running the country, or does he simply focus on what will get him re-elected? In

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:46.120
[Amit Varma]: an ideal democracy, you might imagine that this is a false choice. Surely a politician

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:51.560
[Amit Varma]: in power has to provide good governance to stay in office, right? Well, not in our democracy,

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:56.680
[Amit Varma]: where there is so little connect between power and accountability. Firstly, many good governance

00:01:56.680 --> 00:02:01.680
[Amit Varma]: decisions will show results many years down the road, well beyond the electoral horizon,

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:07.360
[Amit Varma]: and the politician has no incentive to make them now. The deeper structural changes, with

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:11.400
[Amit Varma]: their delayed and invisible benefits, for which no one man will get credit, will not

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:16.400
[Amit Varma]: attract the politician, but the immediate sops or handouts, which look good but perpetuate

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:21.560
[Amit Varma]: the problem, will be more attractive to him. Secondly, we live in an age where narrative

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: is all-powerful. We all live in a world inside our heads that often bears no connection to

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:32.080
[Amit Varma]: the real world outside it. This is enabled and amplified by social media. The most important

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:37.120
[Amit Varma]: skill for a politician, therefore, is to shape these narratives and not change the world.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And that is why it is no surprise that a politician as skilled as Narendra Modi cares more about

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:52.080
[Amit Varma]: optics than about governance. One example of this, the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:57.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:02.320
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:05.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen. The Swachh Bharat Abhiyan sounds amazing, but it's a

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:10.960
[Amit Varma]: classic example of a government scheme whose intentions are noble, but whose outcomes are

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:16.040
[Amit Varma]: small. To explain why this is so, I have as a guest on this episode, Shruti Rajgopalan,

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:20.880
[Amit Varma]: a constitutional economist who teaches economics at Purchase College in New York and who has

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:25.400
[Amit Varma]: been an old friend and a frequent guest on this show. I recorded this episode a few weeks

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:30.020
[Amit Varma]: ago when I was experimenting with this new format of chatting a little bit with my guests

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:34.360
[Amit Varma]: about themselves before we got to the subject at hand. I've since stopped this practice

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:38.480
[Amit Varma]: because listeners gave me feedback that they preferred it if we just got to the point.

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:43.120
[Amit Varma]: But still, this is one of those old recordings from that phase. I enjoyed our entire conversation.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:47.360
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:50.880
[Amit Varma]: If this happens to be the only podcast you listen to, well, you need to listen to some

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:57.400
[Amit Varma]: more. Check out the ones from IVM Podcast who co-produced the show with me. Go to ivmpodcast.com

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:02.360
[Amit Varma]: or download the IVM app and you'll find a host of great Indian podcasts that cover every

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.800
[Amit Varma]: subject you could think of. From the magazine I edit, Pragati, at thinkpragati.com, there

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.000
[Amit Varma]: is the Pragati podcast hosted by Hamsini Hariharan and Pawan Srinath. There is a brilliant Hindi

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.200
[Amit Varma]: podcast Hulia Bhaazi hosted by Pranay Koteswani and Saurabh Chandra. And apart from these

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:24.880
[Amit Varma]: policy podcasts, IVM has shows that cover music, films, finance, sports, sci-fi, tech

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:31.320
[Amit Varma]: and the LGBT community all under one roof or rather all in one app. So download the

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:37.840
[Amit Varma]: IVM podcast app today. Shruti, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Hi, Amit. It's great

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:41.960
[Amit Varma]: to be here. Shruti, by now you're familiar with the custom on the show that I start off

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:48.640
[Amit Varma]: by asking the guest some questions about themselves so that listeners can get to know them better.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:56.240
[Amit Varma]: And last time when we spoke to you, you spoke about your love for economics and law and

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:00.560
[Amit Varma]: what drew you to becoming an economist. And I want to sort of ask what is a follow up

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:05.060
[Amit Varma]: question to that, which is that, you know, I've known you for over 10 years. And one

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:09.480
[Amit Varma]: thing that is safe to say, and that will be obvious to listeners who've heard your previous

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:15.800
[Amit Varma]: episodes is that economics is not just a profession for you or something that you've studied.

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:21.480
[Amit Varma]: You are deeply passionately in love with economics the way some people are with say football.

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:27.600
[Amit Varma]: So was there a specific moment or an aha moment in your life, where things changed for you,

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:31.600
[Amit Varma]: you looked at the world differently because of economics and realized that this was what

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:38.080
[Guest]: you wanted to do? I think I, you know, if I had to have one aha moment, I had a fantastic

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:44.960
[Guest]: professor in DU in my second year. His name is now he's retired. He's Professor Anil Kukradi.

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:50.640
[Guest]: And just like, you know, one of the kindest people I know, and just a really remarkable

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:56.920
[Guest]: teacher. And for the first time, I remember in his class for me, like the world kind of

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:01.600
[Guest]: came into sharp focus. You know how when you wear glasses, and you go to the eye doctor,

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:06.000
[Guest]: they they keep putting different lenses on you. And it's all hazy and bright. And then

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.920
[Guest]: suddenly the world comes into focus and you can read those letters. So that sort of happened

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:17.400
[Guest]: to me when I was a student at DU. He was just an incredible professor. The other part of

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:23.120
[Guest]: it was just reading. You know, I loved economics so much. I read broadly, I read well outside

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:29.760
[Guest]: the curriculum, the DU curriculum was quite sad. So I read a lot. And I think we underestimate

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:35.480
[Guest]: how important simple economic texts are. So Henry Hazlitt and his economics in one lesson

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:41.040
[Guest]: made a big impression. Right? Similarly, Thomas Sowell's work has made a huge impact in how

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:46.240
[Guest]: I think about the world. Frederick Bastiat would be another example, you know, just people

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:53.320
[Guest]: who write complex economic concepts in a simple and very enjoyable way. And slowly I started

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:57.480
[Guest]: seeing economics and everything. The other thing is I'm trained at George Mason, which

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:02.480
[Guest]: is a particular tradition in economics, you know, in terms of public choice, Austrian

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.560
[Guest]: economics and things like that. But one thing at George Mason, I don't know if it's in the

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:11.640
[Guest]: water or the air. Everyone just lives and breeds economics in that department. We see

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:17.640
[Guest]: economics in everything, right from marriage markets to betting markets to political markets.

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:26.600
[Guest]: Everything is an incentive analysis. So I, I guess I found my people. And this is what

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:30.800
[Guest]: I discussed all the way through grad school. And after a point, you know, when you do something

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest]: enough, when you read enough, it just becomes a way of thinking. And people who are close

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.320
[Guest]: to me, my friends, my family, they often make fun of me that I just sort of see economics

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:44.680
[Guest]: and everything. But I don't know if it's a switch that I can turn off now. I think I

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:48.640
[Guest]: think it's been switched on and might stay like this for a long time.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:53.680
[Amit Varma]: No, and I mean, economics is a study of human behavior. So economics is in everything, except

00:07:53.680 --> 00:08:01.040
[Amit Varma]: maybe outer space. But so if an enthusiastic listener of these episodes was to ask that,

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:04.840
[Amit Varma]: hey, economics sounds very interesting. And the economic way of looking at the world is

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:11.480
[Amit Varma]: something that, you know, I want to understand better. And can you recommend, say, three

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:15.840
[Amit Varma]: books or five books, which can help me do that? Like, what are those three books I should

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:20.080
[Amit Varma]: take with me to a holiday resort and lock myself up with and I'll come out a different

00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:24.680
[Amit Varma]: person looking at the world through clear lenses? What would you recommend?

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:29.160
[Guest]: So I would definitely recommend economics in one lesson by Henry Hazlitt, like that

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:34.160
[Guest]: is a beginner's textbook, I think anybody can read it, it doesn't matter whether you've

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:39.640
[Guest]: had any background in economics or social sciences before this, that would be a good

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:42.680
[Guest]: place to start saying pick up any book by Thomas Sowell.

00:08:42.680 --> 00:08:47.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'll interject here and point out that economics in one lesson by Henry Hazlitt,

00:08:47.800 --> 00:08:51.760
[Amit Varma]: one of my favorite books as well is based on an essay by Frederick Bastia inspired by

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:55.920
[Amit Varma]: an essay by Frederick Bastia called that which is seen and that which is not seen, which

00:08:55.920 --> 00:09:02.120
[Amit Varma]: is unseen, which is also the inspiration for this podcast, because that magnificent essay

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:05.720
[Amit Varma]: and it's free online. So just do a Google search that which is seen and that which is

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:08.720
[Guest]: not seen. And yes, sort of talks about

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:14.600
[Guest]: I don't want to reduce economics only to incentive analysis and the analysis of unintended consequences.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:21.800
[Guest]: Absolutely. But I do think economics is very powerful compared to any other discipline

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:26.080
[Guest]: in pointing out what are these unintended or unseen effects. And I don't think any other

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:32.560
[Guest]: discipline comes close. It's like having a superpower, you know. So I really strongly

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:37.840
[Guest]: urge everyone to read both Frederick Bastia, the essay that, you know, Amit mentioned,

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:41.840
[Guest]: and after which the podcast is named, and also Henry Hazlitt's book.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:45.120
[Amit Varma]: Great. And moving on from there, you were mentioning Thomas Sowell.

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:52.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I would say pick up anything by Thomas Sowell. He's great. He's sort of like, I think

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:57.760
[Guest]: the core of good economic ideas is there in pretty much anything he writes. But he's also

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:02.360
[Guest]: someone who's able to see the big picture very clearly. So there's a lot of politics,

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:08.240
[Guest]: there's a lot of culture, there's a lot of history included in how he sees things and

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:13.240
[Guest]: the way he writes. He writes beautifully. So I would definitely recommend him. If you're

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:19.040
[Guest]: not much into reading, and you know, you like videos or interviews and podcasts and things

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:23.720
[Guest]: like that, I would say Amit's podcast is a good place to start. Econ Talk, which Russ

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:28.680
[Guest]: Roberts does is a great place to start. Yeah, Marginal Revolution University, these are

00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:33.400
[Guest]: former professors of mine at George Mason, Tyler Cowen and Alex Tabarrok, who really

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:39.040
[Guest]: don't need any preface or introduction. They do some fantastic videos, their book is really

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:44.360
[Guest]: good. I use their textbook to teach. So these would be like the principles level things.

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:48.760
[Guest]: I would also say, you know, reading a couple of great essays, I think the use of knowledge

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:55.080
[Guest]: in society by Hayek is one of the finest essays I have read on really understanding how the

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:59.640
[Guest]: market system works. Same thing, you know, James Buchanan wrote a fantastic essay called

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:04.840
[Guest]: politics without romance, and introduction to public choice and constitutional economics.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:09.420
[Guest]: And I can provide links for both of them, Amit, and you can just put them up. Those

00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:12.680
[Amit Varma]: are really good sources. We'll have them at the bottom of this episode. In fact, the use

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:16.540
[Amit Varma]: of knowledge in society, in my opinion, is what I keep telling people is one of the two

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:22.300
[Amit Varma]: great essays of the 20th century. Now, let's see how you know, I must agree. Can you guess

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:29.720
[Amit Varma]: which is the other one on my list? The Candlemakers petition? No, 20th century, 20th century, 20th

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:33.760
[Amit Varma]: century. The other one has nothing to do with economics. So I must tell you, but you'll

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:39.800
[Guest]: say aha when I tell you. Yeah, but I'm so one dimensional. I don't know if I know things

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:45.680
[Amit Varma]: outside of economics that you read. You read so broadly. You don't know me at all. It's

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:50.720
[Amit Varma]: politics in the English language by George Orwell. Oh, of course, you've sent it to me.

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:54.360
[Amit Varma]: That's true. That's a fantastic essay. That's a remarkable essay. And both of those, by

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:59.200
[Amit Varma]: the way, on the site, I edit Pragati at thinkpragati.com. We have a section called Historia, where every

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:04.960
[Amit Varma]: month we put up one historic essay, which in over the past months has included the use

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:09.080
[Amit Varma]: of knowledge in society by Hayek, which is such a masterpiece of an essay, politics in

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:14.640
[Amit Varma]: the English language by George Orwell and the essay by B.R. Ambedkar that moved you

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:19.960
[Amit Varma]: so much and that you referred to in our episode about caste, which is when I decided to look

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:24.320
[Amit Varma]: it up because to my shame, I hadn't read that yet. And then we put it up on the site. So

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:30.520
[Guest]: do check out. You know, I just think Ambedkar is one of the, one of the best communicators

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:37.120
[Guest]: I have read. I'm a really big fan of Ambedkar. Our economics and politics don't always align,

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:42.560
[Guest]: but I have never come away from reading Ambedkar without learning anything. And I think he's

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:47.880
[Guest]: the most underappreciated of our framers when it comes to actually reading what he's written,

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:53.880
[Guest]: like he's there in every statue at every street corner. But I do think we need just Ambedkar

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:59.440
[Amit Varma]: to be widely read. So let me ask you a question this time for my own edification rather than

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:04.600
[Amit Varma]: my listeners, which is a genuine question I have, which is that Ambedkar's body of work

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:09.640
[Amit Varma]: is just immense and varied. And it's very common for people to say that you can, if

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:14.080
[Amit Varma]: you read all of his work, you can find justifications for anything in some part of his work or the

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:18.640
[Amit Varma]: other because, you know, he's changed his mind many times. He's gone over so many subjects.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:24.080
[Amit Varma]: But if someone wants a good rigorous introduction to Ambedkar, where should he start? What should

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:25.080
[Amit Varma]: he read?

00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:32.200
[Guest]: I would actually, you know, Ambedkar has this phenomenal ability to write short essays,

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:37.400
[Guest]: letters, give speeches, right? So there are these volumes, it's called Ambedkar writes

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:43.520
[Guest]: and Ambedkar speaks. They are very massive volumes. They were edited by Narendra Jadhav.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:48.640
[Guest]: But if you just pick up a single essay on the monetary system, it's only three pages

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.760
[Guest]: and immensely accessible and readable, right? So I strongly recommend people just Google

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:59.280
[Guest]: Ambedkar's essay on whatever issue they are interested in, whether it's caste, whether

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:03.440
[Guest]: it's taxes, whether it's the Sedition Act, you know, just Google what he's written and

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:09.520
[Guest]: just start reading. I often say this to people that I think Ambedkar would have been fantastic

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:16.840
[Guest]: on Twitter. You know, he came up with like really powerful punchlines, which he delivered

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:22.080
[Guest]: so well when he was giving speeches. So I really miss Ambedkar in present day, not just

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:26.800
[Guest]: because he's such a towering and important figure, but I think his communication skills

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:31.040
[Guest]: were so fantastic, he would have been great on Twitter. So I think just pick up, just

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:35.960
[Guest]: Google Ambedkar's speeches and just start reading Ambedkar in Parliament.

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:40.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm already fantasizing about Ambedkar coming as a guest on the scene in the unseen, but

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:41.640
[Guest]: moving on.

00:14:41.640 --> 00:14:46.600
[Guest]: You know, one of my favorite Ambedkar quotes is the caste system is not just the division

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:51.200
[Guest]: of labor, it's a division of laborers. Can you think of a better way to think about the

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:52.200
[Amit Varma]: caste system?

00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:53.200
[Amit Varma]: Superbly Pithi.

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:59.480
[Guest]: Right? So he's just such a fantastic communicator. I just wish, you know, I know people read

00:14:59.480 --> 00:15:03.800
[Guest]: the 2500 volumes of Gandhi's letters. And you know, I mean, kudos to them. I'm happy

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:08.960
[Guest]: those things are read. But I still think Ambedkar is just under read and underappreciated as

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:14.360
[Guest]: a thinker, you know, not as a political figure or someone who unified the various castes

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:18.760
[Guest]: and who was important in framing the democracy just as an intellectual, a homegrown Indian

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:20.760
[Guest]: intellectual, I think he's very underappreciated.

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:26.720
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. Let's, let's move on now to the subject of this episode, which is something

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:30.240
[Amit Varma]: which would have interested Ambedkar. And I wonder what he would have thought of what's

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:34.600
[Amit Varma]: going on in the country right now. And the subject is a government scheme was started

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:39.720
[Amit Varma]: with the very best of intentions, this Swachh Bharat Abhiyan, of which the scene effect

00:15:39.720 --> 00:15:44.400
[Amit Varma]: as a government keeps tom tomming, of course, is that we have built x number of toilets

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and you know, look what we've and so on and so forth. Tell us a little bit and you've

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.920
[Amit Varma]: written on this yourself in your column in Live Mint, in Mint. And tell us a little bit

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:59.280
[Amit Varma]: more about your feelings about the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:04.400
[Guest]: So you know, public sanitation is incredibly important in modern civilization, right? No

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:10.160
[Guest]: question about that. We have very low levels of public health and sanitation in the rural

00:16:10.160 --> 00:16:16.960
[Guest]: areas. And these have terrible consequences, right? So we have high infant mortality, because

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:23.560
[Guest]: you know, little kids, babies get sick, because the water is polluted or the air is polluted.

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:28.480
[Guest]: If they get diarrhea, they're not able to survive. So there are some really important

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: and terrible consequences for society in terms of not having a good framework for public

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:42.480
[Guest]: health and sanitation. So to that end, I really think it's incredible that this government

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:49.660
[Guest]: has taken on a big initiative and said we really need to pay attention and devote resources

00:16:49.660 --> 00:16:56.800
[Guest]: and political capital towards cleaning India, right? So I can very much get behind the general

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.920
[Guest]: message of Swachh Bharat Abhiyan. I think it's very important. And I don't think it

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:05.840
[Guest]: should be just these four years and you know, Gandhi's 150th birthday. I think we need a

00:17:05.840 --> 00:17:08.280
[Guest]: Swachh Bharat for all times to come.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. And and Shruti in your piece, which is again linked from the bottom of this

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.640
[Amit Varma]: episode is a piece titled, India needs sewage systems, not free toilets. And in your piece,

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:22.720
[Amit Varma]: you say quote, overall, this which is a Swachh Bharat Abhiyan seems like a well intentioned

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:30.480
[Amit Varma]: and sensible initiative, except for one thing, unquote. So now, elaborate sort of on what

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:31.480
[Amit Varma]: that one thing is.

00:17:31.480 --> 00:17:37.040
[Guest]: Yeah. So if you think about what is the end goal to be achieved, if the end goal to be

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:43.680
[Guest]: achieved is to eliminate open defecation, genuinely have, you know, better public sanitation,

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:47.960
[Guest]: I don't think the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan in its current form is going to actually achieve

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:53.840
[Guest]: that goal. If the end goal is that toilets need to be distributed to every household,

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:59.000
[Guest]: I think that goal will be achieved. Right. So let me unpack that a little bit more for

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:05.040
[Guest]: you. Now, what do you really need to eliminate open defecation? So India has one of the highest

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:10.120
[Guest]: levels of open defecation anywhere in the world. In rural areas, it's higher than 65

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:15.360
[Guest]: percent, or at least it was when the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan started. In urban areas, it's

00:18:15.360 --> 00:18:21.000
[Guest]: in, you know, about 20 to 30 percent range. And what we mean by open defecation is people

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:26.800
[Guest]: just go out and do their business in the open. Now, you live in Mumbai, so you must have

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:32.720
[Guest]: seen people squatting next to the train lines in the morning. Right. This is a very prevalent

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:37.400
[Guest]: site in urban India. In rural India, they go into, you know, farmland and things like

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:45.520
[Guest]: that. And this is a very big problem because it's difficult to clean up in cultures that

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:53.400
[Guest]: have a lot of open defecation. All the diseases that small babies, women, actually pretty

00:18:53.400 --> 00:19:00.000
[Guest]: much people of any age have happens because the basic water system is polluted. And that

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:06.480
[Guest]: is because all this, you know, excreta has not been treated because it's open defecation.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: So this is a very fundamental problem. It has massive health and productivity consequences.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:19.280
[Guest]: It has very large emotional consequences because it is terrible. I mean, every infant that

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:24.720
[Guest]: can be saved should be saved. And the levels of infant mortality we have in UP and Bihar

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:29.800
[Guest]: and things like that are quite, quite terrible and embarrassing in the modern world. So this

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:35.160
[Guest]: has very deep, important consequences for India. Now, how do you solve for this? How

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:41.320
[Guest]: does anyone solve for this? One way of solving for this is we build waste management systems.

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:46.960
[Guest]: And you know, you and I have had lots of conversations about what is the role of government, you

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:51.040
[Guest]: know, what should government do in society at the local, state, federal level and so

00:19:51.040 --> 00:19:57.840
[Guest]: on. And I think one really important public good that the government must provide is a

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:04.520
[Guest]: good waste management system. It is very costly, difficult and problematic for every household

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:09.200
[Guest]: to have its own waste management system. Frankly, it's also quite like, you know, unappealing

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:15.520
[Guest]: and a little bit disgusting. So the role of government should be to design waste management

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:21.360
[Guest]: systems where all you need to do is every household is plugged into that system. Right.

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:27.600
[Guest]: So in urban areas, this can be a functional sewage system. Right. In rural areas, it could

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:32.720
[Guest]: be something on a smaller scale. It might be difficult to build large scale sewage systems

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:38.080
[Guest]: because hamlets might be far apart. But you can still have some kind of a simpler version

00:20:38.080 --> 00:20:44.920
[Guest]: of a sewage system with, you know, an end area where you collect the refuse in a septic

00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:50.560
[Guest]: tank or take it to another location before you treat it and so on. And this service has

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:54.800
[Guest]: not been provided, not just by this government, but any government in the past. So your larger

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:59.480
[Amit Varma]: point is that, look, it seems natural that people are doing open defecation. And it seems

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:03.360
[Amit Varma]: natural that, hey, if you build toilets, they'll have toilets to go to. They'll go there. But

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:07.040
[Amit Varma]: then the point is, once they do their business inside the toilet, what happens then? What

00:21:07.040 --> 00:21:12.920
[Guest]: happens to the waste as it were? And that is what you need to build. Exactly. So now

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:16.880
[Guest]: the way I think about this Swachh Bharat Abhiyan is it's a good initiative. But what it's doing

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:22.080
[Guest]: is it's solving the last mile problem. Right. My point of view is, if we had functional

00:21:22.080 --> 00:21:27.480
[Guest]: sewage systems in urban areas and waste management systems in rural areas, it is actually not

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:31.640
[Guest]: that expensive to construct a toilet or a latrine. In fact, the last mile problem would

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:37.280
[Guest]: take care of itself. Exactly. So India is already at a level of development where most

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:42.160
[Guest]: people don't need a toilet subsidy if there is a waste management system that they can

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:46.440
[Guest]: easily access. Right. And yes, there might be 20 percent of the people who still need

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:51.120
[Guest]: a toilet subsidy. And I think at that stage, I would very much encourage any government,

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:56.480
[Guest]: state, federal, local to, you know, help build subsidized toilets and so on. But right now,

00:21:56.480 --> 00:22:00.560
[Guest]: we are actually creating a new kind of problem. OK, and it's funny. We were talking about

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:09.040
[Guest]: Ambedkar just a few moments ago. So now India has deep persistence of the caste system.

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:15.720
[Guest]: Right. One very important part of the caste system is ritual purity and what certain castes

00:22:15.720 --> 00:22:21.480
[Guest]: consider polluting behavior and so on and so forth. Right. Many of the historically

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:27.600
[Guest]: oppressed castes were oppressed either into doing all these distasteful jobs or were oppressed

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:33.200
[Guest]: because they took on these jobs. Right. So the lowest caste in society, in fact, these

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:38.240
[Guest]: are castes that weren't even allowed to live in the village system. They were outcasts

00:22:38.240 --> 00:22:42.640
[Guest]: to see what is now called manual scavenging. Right. They were manual scavengers. What they

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:47.200
[Guest]: would do is there would be an outhouse at the back where people did their business and

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:51.200
[Guest]: it would be collected and these people would not even be allowed to enter the house. They

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:55.240
[Guest]: would just come from the back. They would pick up all the human refuse and they would

00:22:55.240 --> 00:23:00.520
[Guest]: take it literally like carry a tank or a basket on the head and go to the next house. Right.

00:23:00.520 --> 00:23:07.080
[Guest]: Now, you can imagine how terrible it is to have a profession dedicated to having to carry

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:14.240
[Guest]: someone else's feces in your hands. Right. And now you can also imagine that in a culture

00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:19.360
[Guest]: which is so obsessed with the caste system and ritual purity, how groups would treat

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:25.440
[Guest]: people who actually engage in this activity as as a form of livelihood. Manual scavengers

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:33.960
[Guest]: were treated abominably in India. Right. And the system came about simply because there

00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:39.800
[Guest]: was no other waste management system. So now, if you think about the long term consequences

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.160
[Guest]: of having only a latrine in the house and not a waste management system, what we're

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:49.080
[Guest]: doing is we're bringing back manual scavenging. It's actually coming back. So now there are

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:54.080
[Guest]: two types of consequences of having toilets, but no waste management system. One consequence

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:59.600
[Guest]: is people are just using those toilets as storage units or, you know, to keep your provisions

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:02.920
[Guest]: or wash your clothes or something. And they actually still do their business out in the

00:24:02.920 --> 00:24:08.440
[Guest]: open. Right. So toilets are there, but open defecation hasn't reduced. The other group

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:13.240
[Guest]: is they do decide to use the latrine or the toilet that has been built by the government,

00:24:13.240 --> 00:24:20.480
[Guest]: but they don't want to touch anything to do with their own feces. So now what happens

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:25.960
[Guest]: is you perpetuate the caste system by bringing back manual scavenging, which, by the way,

00:24:25.960 --> 00:24:30.760
[Guest]: was abolished many decades ago in India. So that is one of the unintended or the unseen

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:35.840
[Guest]: consequences of building toilets without building sewage systems. What people really want. So

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:41.880
[Guest]: you. OK, so let me put this in perspective. In an ideal world, you want people not to

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest]: have all these ridiculous ideas about ritual purity. You want people to make use of latrines.

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:53.000
[Guest]: You want people not to openly defecate. OK, that's the ideal world. We don't live in the

00:24:53.000 --> 00:25:01.000
[Guest]: ideal world. We live in a deeply. Backward society from the point of view of caste. Right.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:07.200
[Guest]: And it is so persistent and it is impossible to break down overnight. People who have these

00:25:07.200 --> 00:25:12.960
[Guest]: kinds of values about ritual purity, though I don't subscribe or endorse any of them,

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:18.480
[Guest]: they would actually use the latrine or the toilet that was built at home. Were it connected

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:24.280
[Guest]: to a sewage system where you could just flush the refuse away? Right. And that system we

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:29.640
[Guest]: don't have right now. And until we get that system, you're going to have lots of toilets,

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:33.360
[Guest]: but you're not going to solve the public health and sanitation problem. And if you do manage

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:37.240
[Guest]: to solve the public health and sanitation problem a little bit, you're going to have

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:41.000
[Guest]: a whole class of workers who are oppressed once again because of manual scavenging. In

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:45.040
[Amit Varma]: fact, you know, that's a very unintuitive conclusion in the sense that a sewage system

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:49.160
[Amit Varma]: is not just something that will help with hygiene and public health, but it will also

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:54.920
[Guest]: help in eliminating the caste system. It really would. In some small way. In some small way.

00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:59.560
[Guest]: And at the very least, even if it doesn't eliminate it, at least it won't perpetuate

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:06.320
[Guest]: it. Right. Right. We really have to worry about, and especially at the rural level,

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:12.440
[Guest]: you know, in places like UP and Bihar, where the caste system is very persistent, open

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:19.160
[Guest]: defecation is very persistent, and you have very low levels of, you know, economic growth.

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:24.840
[Amit Varma]: This is the trifecta for caste oppression. Right. And we'll take a slight literary digression

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:28.560
[Amit Varma]: here. Have you heard of Pablo Neruda, the poet from Chile? Yes. Yeah. So there is a

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:32.800
[Amit Varma]: story of Neruda and you mentioned, you know, outhouses and how these scavengers were looked

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:37.260
[Amit Varma]: upon as almost subhuman in a sense. And there is a story of how when Neruda was a young

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:42.320
[Amit Varma]: man in his 20s, and is related by Neruda himself in his autobiography, if I remember correctly.

00:26:42.320 --> 00:26:49.160
[Amit Varma]: And Neruda was posted to Sri Lanka as some sort of ambassadorial kind of, you know, some

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:54.440
[Amit Varma]: part of their foreign office or whatever. And he lived in a house which had an outhouse

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:59.280
[Amit Varma]: at the back for doing the business. And he was curious about how every day I do my business,

00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:03.120
[Amit Varma]: but when I come the next morning, it's pick and span, it's clean. So one day he decided

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:10.600
[Amit Varma]: to find out. And he saw this dark skinned lady walking up taking his refuse and just

00:27:10.600 --> 00:27:15.920
[Amit Varma]: going away. And for some reason, being of a poetic temperament or whatever, he fell

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:19.800
[Amit Varma]: in love or rather one should say he fell in lust with her. And he waited like that for

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:24.480
[Amit Varma]: three, four days, and she would come at the crack of dawn, take away his business as it

00:27:24.480 --> 00:27:29.080
[Amit Varma]: were, and just go away. And then one day, he just held her by the hand, took her inside

00:27:29.080 --> 00:27:33.680
[Amit Varma]: to his bedroom, and he had sex with her. And it was obviously rape, because he described

00:27:33.680 --> 00:27:38.840
[Amit Varma]: how she just lay inert with no expression on her face and not even resisting, which

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:45.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of tells you about a the power dynamic involved and be also the fact that these people

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:51.800
[Amit Varma]: were considered subhuman. So it didn't, you know, they had no agency, and there was no

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:57.720
[Amit Varma]: trace of empathy in him, as you would expect for another human being, which is why decades

00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:02.840
[Amit Varma]: later, when he's a renowned Nobel Prize winning poet, he actually writes about this openly

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:09.320
[Amit Varma]: without any trace of remorse in his autobiography, which which is just remarkably shocking. And

00:28:09.320 --> 00:28:13.480
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, tells you so much about the man himself. I mean, one can't read his poetry

00:28:13.480 --> 00:28:19.360
[Amit Varma]: in the same light after that. But it also illustrates what you were saying about the

00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:25.600
[Amit Varma]: inequities of the caste system. And to some extent, those inequities being perpetuated

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:32.480
[Amit Varma]: or being made explicit by sort of the physical logistics of this outhouse outside and the

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:38.600
[Guest]: person who comes and collects human refuse before people wake up.

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:44.000
[Guest]: And you know, I mean, of course, the men are treated terribly, the women are always treated

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:50.960
[Guest]: worse, there is a very, very big problem of rape against by upper caste, I say upper caste

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:54.960
[Guest]: and lower caste, not because I think these are upper or lower caste, it's just, that's

00:28:54.960 --> 00:29:00.360
[Guest]: the vocabulary use. But people who think that they're of an upper caste, there's a lot of

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:06.320
[Guest]: rape of Dalit women by people higher up in the power structure. But there's also a rape

00:29:06.320 --> 00:29:11.360
[Guest]: problem with open defecation. Exactly. You know, women have to go outside at like 4-430

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:17.040
[Guest]: in the morning, it's dark, there is a lot of sexual abuse that happens because we haven't

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:23.000
[Guest]: provided even the most basic types of sanitation system so that women can be safe.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:26.680
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. And this is a point you'd recommended I read the superb book which I ended up doing

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:31.040
[Amit Varma]: called Where India Goes by Diane Coffey and Dean Spears. And they make pretty much the

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:37.560
[Amit Varma]: same points about open defecation and ritual purity that you've just explained.

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:42.680
[Guest]: And you know, that book is really fantastic, for multiple reasons, because the authors

00:29:42.680 --> 00:29:48.520
[Guest]: never came to the subject, wanting to write about the caste system, they came to the subject

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:54.360
[Guest]: as health economists, right? They were trying to understand high levels of infant mortality

00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:59.160
[Guest]: and just, you know, the health problems in these developing areas. And what they discovered

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:04.160
[Guest]: was, oh, there are all these toilets being built. But you would think people would just

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:11.160
[Guest]: jump at it. And it would be a superior alternative to open defecation. But it's actually an inferior

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:16.120
[Guest]: alternative to open defecation, because they live in a world where the caste system persists.

00:30:16.120 --> 00:30:22.280
[Guest]: And they are not allowed to touch their own refuse. And if they do, then there are questions

00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:26.840
[Guest]: about their purity, and they have polluted themselves and things like that. And what

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:33.840
[Guest]: I love about the book is, it places what is a development or an economic problem, beautifully

00:30:33.840 --> 00:30:39.600
[Guest]: in the social context within which we are trying to solve that problem. So you can't

00:30:39.600 --> 00:30:45.920
[Guest]: have solutions to these problems by ignoring what is the local or the social context, right?

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:51.880
[Guest]: The caste problem in UP, you don't have this problem in fishermen hamlets in Tamil Nadu.

00:30:51.880 --> 00:30:58.640
[Guest]: They are perfectly fine. They have eliminated open defecation. And they don't have this

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:02.880
[Guest]: problem of ritual purity and things like that. They may have other caste issues, but this

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:08.920
[Guest]: is not one that is highly persistent among them. So I think we really need to think about

00:31:08.920 --> 00:31:13.920
[Guest]: public health, public sanitation, in a very local contextual manner. And to that extent,

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:18.920
[Guest]: I would I would recommend everyone reads this book. It was my pick for the best book written

00:31:18.920 --> 00:31:24.080
[Guest]: last year. The book is called Where India Goes. It's very accessible.

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:27.080
[Amit Varma]: It's a book called Where India Goes by Diane Coffey and Dean Spears. And there'll be a

