[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm talking with Shruti Rajgopalan and we're discussing

00:32:58.600 --> 00:33:06.520
[Amit Varma]: India Swachh Bharat Abhiyan, which achieved the very feel good, look nice kind of outcome

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:12.040
[Amit Varma]: of building a huge number of toilets across the country. And you would assume that that

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:18.520
[Amit Varma]: helped with solving our sanitation problems, which are also massive public health problems.

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:24.400
[Amit Varma]: Because as Shruti explained, open defecation leads to a public health crisis, it affects

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:29.240
[Amit Varma]: child mortality, kids actually dying much younger than they otherwise would. And it's

00:33:29.240 --> 00:33:34.320
[Amit Varma]: a humanitarian issue. And you would think logically that if people don't have toilets

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:37.080
[Amit Varma]: in their home, you're building them toilets, that's surely great. But as Shruti pointed

00:33:37.080 --> 00:33:41.560
[Amit Varma]: out, the unseen side of this is that with the toilet, you're just solving the last mile

00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:46.400
[Amit Varma]: problem that show the guy can go to the toilet and do his job. But what happens after that?

00:33:46.400 --> 00:33:51.280
[Amit Varma]: What happens with, let's say the refuse that he's left there, if you don't have a good

00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:55.400
[Amit Varma]: waste disposal system, if you don't have a good sewage system, then that necessarily

00:33:55.400 --> 00:34:01.880
[Amit Varma]: means that his refuse has to be cleaned either by himself or by somebody else. And that has

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:08.080
[Amit Varma]: led to a return of manual scavenging and some of the worst of the caste system as an unintended

00:34:08.080 --> 00:34:14.680
[Amit Varma]: consequence. And therefore the answer lies in building sewage systems and waste disposal

00:34:14.680 --> 00:34:20.600
[Amit Varma]: systems and the toilets will take care of themselves once the infrastructure is in place.

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:23.160
[Amit Varma]: Is that an accurate summation, Shruti?

00:34:23.160 --> 00:34:28.560
[Guest]: Absolutely. I would also add one line that you know, we can also think about education,

00:34:28.560 --> 00:34:34.640
[Guest]: educating people about the myths of all this ritual purity nonsense. So I would also support

00:34:34.640 --> 00:34:41.320
[Guest]: educating people about the caste system and why, you know, manually pumping out or cleaning

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:46.920
[Guest]: out your latrine doesn't make you impure and actually protects your family better. So I

00:34:46.920 --> 00:34:51.160
[Guest]: would say that is also a good way to go. But our education system is so badly broken, I'm

00:34:51.160 --> 00:34:52.160
[Amit Varma]: not holding my breath.

00:34:52.160 --> 00:34:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And even apart from that certain religious and traditional beliefs, whatever you call

00:34:55.960 --> 00:35:01.240
[Amit Varma]: them, are often immune to education, because we are still a deeply superstitious society

00:35:01.240 --> 00:35:06.800
[Amit Varma]: with all kinds of ludicrously irrational beliefs about everyday life.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:12.560
[Guest]: Absolutely. And you know, of all the things, this is generally so unpleasant. I don't have

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:17.800
[Guest]: any of these ritual purity beliefs, right? But this is generally such an unpleasant area

00:35:17.800 --> 00:35:24.000
[Guest]: that any excuse you can get to not have to touch feces is, you know, people are just

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: going to sort of jump on it. I'm just talking from a human nature perspective, right? No

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:31.480
[Guest]: one is very excited about manually pumping out a used latrine.

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:37.200
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I would say that, you know, invoking natural selection that a disgust towards feces

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:41.280
[Amit Varma]: is selected for because obviously, if you handle your own feces, you're likelier to

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:45.720
[Amit Varma]: fall ill and so on and so forth that affects your survival. So it's selected for its naturalist

00:35:45.720 --> 00:35:48.840
[Amit Varma]: instinctive and there's nothing wrong with it. But the point is that if you just had

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:54.320
[Amit Varma]: a good waste disposable waste disposal system, you wouldn't need to touch your own feces

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:58.600
[Amit Varma]: or to get someone else to do it. You just pull the flush. And exactly.

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:02.680
[Guest]: And also a question of equipment and training and things like that, right? There are there

00:36:02.680 --> 00:36:07.840
[Guest]: are many solutions between open defecation and a sophisticated sewage system that New

00:36:07.840 --> 00:36:13.680
[Guest]: York City has. So there are many intermediate levels of waste management systems which require

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:20.400
[Guest]: resources and local context and training the, you know, municipality workers on how to use

00:36:20.400 --> 00:36:25.040
[Guest]: them. And we don't have we don't pay any attention to any of those things.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:29.680
[Amit Varma]: So we are 71 years past independence. Why haven't we done it yet? Like, let's not talk

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:33.880
[Amit Varma]: about this government or that government or Nehru versus Modi. It's been 71 years. Everyone's

00:36:33.880 --> 00:36:37.220
[Amit Varma]: had a shot at it. Not much movement has happened. Why is that?

00:36:37.220 --> 00:36:41.740
[Guest]: So the number one reason and you know, Amit, you and I have spoken about this personally

00:36:41.740 --> 00:36:48.080
[Guest]: and also on the podcast. The number one reason is we, until very recently, did not have a

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:53.320
[Guest]: functional layer of local government. These are problems that are meant to be resolved

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:58.000
[Guest]: by the local government. You can't have the central government trying to figure out that

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:03.160
[Guest]: in the south bungalow area, you know, do we need to build a new sewage system or extend

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:09.360
[Guest]: the pipeline for the new building to be connected? These are local problems. They need local

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:14.920
[Guest]: solutions. We didn't have local government. That is a very, very big part of the problem

00:37:14.920 --> 00:37:20.280
[Guest]: and extremely underappreciated, especially in rural areas. Now, we've had a local government

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:25.440
[Guest]: system for about 25 years. We just celebrated the 25th anniversary of, you know, the panchayati

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:30.600
[Guest]: raj and urban local body, the constitutional amendments, which were the 73rd and 74th amendment.

00:37:30.600 --> 00:37:35.720
[Guest]: So we created a layer of local government, but we didn't give them any responsibility,

00:37:35.720 --> 00:37:42.240
[Guest]: nor did we give them any revenue raising authority. You and I have done a podcast on this before.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:47.320
[Guest]: So basically, you have local governments today, but they have no budgets, right? And the state

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:52.640
[Guest]: government has just held on to power and revenue, and they haven't devolved responsibility or

00:37:52.640 --> 00:37:58.840
[Guest]: the budgets to these local governments. So I would say the number one blame sort of I

00:37:58.840 --> 00:38:04.520
[Guest]: would place on why we don't have good local public sanitation systems is because we never

00:38:04.520 --> 00:38:08.480
[Guest]: had good local government, we never invested in that layer of government.

00:38:08.480 --> 00:38:12.640
[Amit Varma]: So we've done a podcast on this earlier, which is one of my favourite episodes. In fact,

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:17.040
[Amit Varma]: it's an episode on urban governance, if you just go to seen unseen.in, you can find that

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:21.080
[Amit Varma]: in the archival episodes, I don't remember the episode number. But let me quickly try

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:27.040
[Amit Varma]: and sum up the sort of insights that you gave us in that episode, where your whole point

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:31.400
[Amit Varma]: was that when it comes to local governance, urban or otherwise, there is a disconnect

00:38:31.400 --> 00:38:36.560
[Amit Varma]: between power and accountability, who's accountable to us, your local corporator, and so on, they're

00:38:36.560 --> 00:38:41.080
[Amit Varma]: all accountable to you, you vote for them, they depend on your votes to get get to office.

00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:46.160
[Amit Varma]: But who has a power over you, these guys don't really have much power, because local government

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:51.440
[Amit Varma]: in our constitution and in our system, simply hasn't been given that much power, all the

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:55.360
[Amit Varma]: power is really with the state government. And when it comes to, for example, a city

00:38:55.360 --> 00:38:59.640
[Amit Varma]: like Mumbai, the state government is not so accountable to you, because it depend more

00:38:59.640 --> 00:39:05.160
[Amit Varma]: on rural votes or votes from outside the city, and on different constituencies, like there'll

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:10.280
[Amit Varma]: be a constituency of farmers, and so on and so forth. And when you have local problems

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:14.880
[Amit Varma]: that need to be solved, the person who is accountable to you doesn't have the power

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:19.880
[Amit Varma]: to solve them. And the people who do have the power and the budgets to affect your lives

00:39:19.880 --> 00:39:26.040
[Amit Varma]: don't care about you, because your vote doesn't matter to them. Is that an accurate summation?

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:29.440
[Guest]: That's an accurate summation. I would also add one one last point, which is, you know,

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:33.440
[Guest]: you live in Andheri. Andheri doesn't have much of an open defecation problem, as far

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:38.520
[Guest]: as I know. It has other problems, garbage collection, poor sidewalks, you know, those

00:39:38.520 --> 00:39:44.080
[Guest]: kinds of problems. So if you were to now talk about open defecation, maybe that's a problem

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:49.960
[Guest]: in rural Maharashtra. It's very difficult for people like Amit living in Andheri to

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:55.300
[Guest]: coordinate with people in rural Maharashtra and put together a platform when their local

00:39:55.300 --> 00:40:01.480
[Guest]: problems are so different. They are going to be asking for really basic things, right?

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:05.860
[Guest]: Like how can we secure a well, and you are asking for far more sophisticated things.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:10.640
[Guest]: So not only does your vote matter less at the state level, it's far more difficult and

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:16.680
[Guest]: far less likely to organize different groups because they have very different local problems

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:18.840
[Amit Varma]: which are highly contextual.

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:22.960
[Amit Varma]: So the ideal system of government, therefore, is obviously as local as possible. And we

00:40:22.960 --> 00:40:26.800
[Amit Varma]: are planning to do an episode on Panchayati Raj. So, you know, watch out for that in the

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:31.520
[Amit Varma]: coming weeks. But the ideal government is as local as possible. So people within an

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:37.360
[Amit Varma]: area know what their immediate concerns are, and they can make sure that their government,

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:41.960
[Amit Varma]: which is accountable to them, will actually do those things. And for that, they need to

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:47.320
[Amit Varma]: have the power to do those things. And that power has never been devolved to local governments

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:51.080
[Amit Varma]: at all, because the central and the state governments, obviously, anybody who has power

00:40:51.080 --> 00:40:53.200
[Amit Varma]: is hesitant to give away a part of it.

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:58.120
[Guest]: Exactly. So in one sense, you know, Prime Minister Modi and his team, which is running

00:40:58.120 --> 00:41:03.880
[Guest]: the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan, they are definitely quite sensible. They know that they can't

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:09.240
[Guest]: build waste management systems. So they say we'll build toilets instead. Right. So they

00:41:09.240 --> 00:41:13.520
[Guest]: are actually quite sensible in that they are trying to solve the problem that you can actually

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:18.360
[Guest]: implement at the central level. So to that extent, the program is an enormous success.

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:22.640
[Guest]: But the program is an enormous failure if the goal is actually public sanitation and

00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:27.120
[Guest]: public health. Right. Because it's never going to solve it unless you have local partners

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:33.160
[Guest]: who can help convert this network of latrines into a sensible waste management system. So

00:41:33.160 --> 00:41:39.000
[Guest]: that is really the core of the conundrum that the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan poses. It's a great

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:43.760
[Guest]: idea. It's important to solve the last mile problem. But you have to solve the last mile

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:51.160
[Guest]: problem last. And you can't ask PM Modi to solve the initial first hundred mile problem

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:55.440
[Guest]: because it simply can't be done at the centralized level. It has to be devolved to the local

00:41:55.440 --> 00:41:56.440
[Amit Varma]: level.

00:41:56.440 --> 00:41:59.840
[Amit Varma]: I'll both back you up and take a cynical view of that. My criticism of the Modi government

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:04.080
[Amit Varma]: right from 2014 is that they have never got into governance mode. They have continued

00:42:04.080 --> 00:42:08.080
[Amit Varma]: in campaigning mode, which they are incredibly good at. And pretty much everything they do

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:12.920
[Amit Varma]: at the level of governance is for the sake of optics. So even in the Swachh Bharat campaign,

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:16.680
[Amit Varma]: is great optics that, hey, we've built so many million toilets and it looks great and

00:42:16.680 --> 00:42:21.160
[Amit Varma]: you can declare it a success. But they don't really care beyond that, which I think is

00:42:21.160 --> 00:42:25.600
[Amit Varma]: a cross against them. At the same time, I'll agree with you and say that as far as solving

00:42:25.600 --> 00:42:29.800
[Amit Varma]: the deeper problem of public sanitation is concerned, that yes, the central government

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:34.880
[Amit Varma]: can't really do much, you're spot on about that. But at the same time, the central government

00:42:34.880 --> 00:42:40.640
[Amit Varma]: could accept the structural problem, which is preventing that the whole issue that local

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:45.000
[Amit Varma]: governments don't have enough power, or enough power hasn't devolved down to local governments,

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:49.080
[Amit Varma]: and do something about solving that structural problem, which is not something I see either.

00:42:49.080 --> 00:42:53.600
[Guest]: Absolutely. There, I must agree with you both the central and the state level. And here

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:59.800
[Guest]: I pose even more emphasis on state level legislatures and executive, which is they really need to

00:42:59.800 --> 00:43:05.600
[Guest]: get their act together and recognize that local governance problems can never be resolved

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:11.800
[Guest]: at that level of centrality. And you know, Indian states are larger than most European

00:43:11.800 --> 00:43:18.080
[Guest]: and Latin American countries in terms of size and population. So even at the state level,

00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:25.040
[Guest]: it's like trying to build a, you know, a sewage system for Brazil, or Germany. So it's not

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:30.400
[Guest]: like the state level is some chota level in India, right? It's still a very, very complex

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:37.800
[Guest]: system with very large area and very large population and diversity in population, lots

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:42.880
[Guest]: and lots of local issues. So I think there needs to be a recognition of this in India,

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:47.800
[Guest]: that the level of complexity that the Indian polity poses, and I don't see any of that

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:51.480
[Guest]: at the central or the state level at this point in terms of devolution.

00:43:51.480 --> 00:43:55.880
[Amit Varma]: And another thing that we don't see and explain to me why that is so, is that normally you

00:43:55.880 --> 00:44:00.600
[Amit Varma]: would imagine that when there is such a far reaching problem of public health, when you

00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:05.360
[Amit Varma]: know, babies die younger than they need to, when, you know, it's a humanitarian crisis

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:09.360
[Amit Varma]: in a manner of speaking that's continued on for more than seven decades, you would imagine

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:14.400
[Amit Varma]: that citizens would take a stand and they would be constant more chars and her nose

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:19.800
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth till something is done about it. But even citizens don't seem to

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:27.160
[Guest]: excuse the phrasing give a shit about this. So, you know, I find citizen apathy is very

00:44:27.160 --> 00:44:33.520
[Guest]: contextual. You know, my parents recently moved to a condo building in Noida, you know,

00:44:33.520 --> 00:44:38.800
[Guest]: it's all the typical things you would associate with a middle class or an upper middle class

00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:45.840
[Guest]: condo society, right? It's got all these buildings and they have a whole co-op and a voting system

00:44:45.840 --> 00:44:49.280
[Guest]: where, you know, all the people get together and they raise their voice over daily issues.

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:55.640
[Guest]: When I go to one of those meetings, it's like my blood pressure goes up. People are so passionate

00:44:55.640 --> 00:45:01.320
[Guest]: about, you know, should this be the entry gate and the exit gate or only the entry gate,

00:45:01.320 --> 00:45:04.720
[Guest]: right? How many speed breakers should we have in front of which of the buildings should

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:10.200
[Guest]: you have the speed breaker so that, you know, children are not faced with the fast traffic

00:45:10.200 --> 00:45:15.120
[Guest]: coming in and outside the parking garage? Should you have a water desalination plant?

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:20.800
[Guest]: Because that's a big problem in Noida. People are deeply passionate, like deeply passionate.

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:27.720
[Guest]: They shout, they yell, they politic, they, you know, have parties with other association

00:45:27.720 --> 00:45:32.240
[Guest]: members where they say, this is Noida, they probably murder as well. Yeah. So this is

00:45:32.240 --> 00:45:38.080
[Guest]: incredible. And when I think about why isn't it that these people are doing this with the

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:41.040
[Guest]: Noida Municipal Corporation, they're like upper middle class people who don't even go

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:48.640
[Guest]: to vote. It's because they pay condo association fees. And the condo president lives next door,

00:45:48.640 --> 00:45:52.840
[Guest]: right? And the whole board membership lives next door. So if your governance problems

00:45:52.840 --> 00:45:57.240
[Guest]: aren't solved, you just pick up the phone and go badmouth them. And if they are solved,

00:45:57.240 --> 00:46:02.880
[Guest]: then you host a dinner party for them. Right. And you pay your fees. There's a huge link

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:08.320
[Guest]: between what you pay and what you get. The feedback mechanisms are very tight at the

00:46:08.320 --> 00:46:14.240
[Guest]: local level. Right. So I think we need to put citizen apathy in context. Of course,

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:18.240
[Guest]: there is citizen apathy in Andheri. No one knows the name of the municipal corporator

00:46:18.240 --> 00:46:22.440
[Guest]: because no one has to, because he can never solve these problems or she can never solve

00:46:22.440 --> 00:46:29.360
[Guest]: these problems. Whereas the president of the condo association in Noida can and does.

00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:33.560
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, the residents of the condo association in Noida, what they are

00:46:33.560 --> 00:46:37.080
[Amit Varma]: doing is simply they're demanding a bank for their buck, they pay those fees, they want

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:43.360
[Amit Varma]: those services. And yet somehow at the level of the citizen, we seem to have this, we disassociated

00:46:43.360 --> 00:46:49.240
[Amit Varma]: ourselves from the fact that we also pay a constant cost for government and yet we don't

00:46:49.240 --> 00:46:54.640
[Amit Varma]: demand enough in return. We take taxes for granted, even though they are coercive and

00:46:54.640 --> 00:46:59.640
[Amit Varma]: mostly highly unfair. And we don't get any bank for our buck. And also we take the government

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:04.840
[Amit Varma]: for granted. And we assume that, you know, we behave essentially like subjects that whatever

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:08.580
[Amit Varma]: is done for us, you know, it's great, it's a bonus. But otherwise, we don't stand up

00:47:08.580 --> 00:47:13.440
[Guest]: and demand our rights enough. But even there, Amit, there's a centralization problem. You

00:47:13.440 --> 00:47:18.280
[Guest]: don't know who you're paying tax to, you don't know where it's going. There is a Swachh Bharat

00:47:18.280 --> 00:47:22.880
[Guest]: cess that goes to the central government, right? If your local municipal corporator

00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:28.880
[Guest]: and the local municipal body had the authority to levy taxes and raise taxes, you will also

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:33.600
[Guest]: be marching in Nandheri. Or if not you, a bunch of other people, right? Saying, dude,

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:39.080
[Guest]: you raised our local taxes, and you didn't clean the garbage. So you really need to think

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:42.920
[Guest]: small at this level. Right. And so,

00:47:42.920 --> 00:47:46.600
[Amit Varma]: your point is that the apathy is rational, because we know that we can't do anything

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:50.680
[Amit Varma]: anywhere. Protest is pointless. So people we can protest to are powerless to do anything

00:47:50.680 --> 00:47:55.120
[Amit Varma]: about it. And your argument is that we would be less apathetic if the structure of government

00:47:55.120 --> 00:47:56.120
[Amit Varma]: changed.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:48:02.720
[Guest]: Exactly. So I don't see this level of apathy. I mean, look at Indians on Twitter, look at

00:48:02.720 --> 00:48:07.680
[Guest]: Indians at their dinner parties, look at Indians at their condo association meetings, they

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:12.440
[Guest]: don't come across as apathetic. In fact, you know, the Amartya Sen version of the Indian,

00:48:12.440 --> 00:48:19.440
[Guest]: the argumentative Indian, that is a much more fitting description, because we discuss, we

00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:22.520
[Guest]: fight, right, passionately, emotionally.

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:25.880
[Amit Varma]: On Twitter, you don't have the argumentative Indian, you have the abusive Indian or the

00:48:25.880 --> 00:48:26.880
[Amit Varma]: virtue signaling Indian.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:27.880
[Guest]: You have all sorts of Indians, right?

00:48:27.880 --> 00:48:28.880
[Guest]: Yeah, it's very hard to find a good argument.

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:34.880
[Guest]: But what I mean is, it is not a, it's not fundamentally, we're not culturally apathetic,

00:48:34.880 --> 00:48:41.600
[Guest]: that Indians are apathetic. I think it's contextual, you're apathetic when you know that your voice

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:46.200
[Guest]: will not be heard, and there is going to be no feedback coming from the other side. So

00:48:46.200 --> 00:48:52.640
[Guest]: you try once or twice, and then you give up. And when your voice can be heard, you do use

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:57.320
[Guest]: your voice and you do demand change. So I think we really need to think about structure

00:48:57.320 --> 00:49:01.920
[Guest]: of government and, you know, just better systems of local governance. And, you know, at the

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:06.780
[Guest]: local level, you can also experiment more, right? Andheri East and Andheri West are large

00:49:06.780 --> 00:49:10.320
[Guest]: enough that you can have two different kinds of local governments, and then you can see

00:49:10.320 --> 00:49:15.200
[Guest]: which one worked better. So you can have more experimentation, you can have a greater level

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:21.360
[Guest]: of addressing the local problem in the local context, you can experiment with tax rates,

00:49:21.360 --> 00:49:26.800
[Guest]: right? You have far more competition, political competition at the local level. And we have

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:33.600
[Guest]: basically not capitalized on this incredibly important political mechanism.

00:49:33.600 --> 00:49:37.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Andheri West and Andheri East together have more than four times the population of

00:49:37.720 --> 00:49:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Iceland. I pointed this out recently after Iceland held Argentina to a draw, I think

00:49:43.680 --> 00:49:47.320
[Guest]: it was on Twitter. Yeah, not even half as good a football team. Yeah, no, no, I didn't

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:50.680
[Amit Varma]: even mention that. I just said to put it into perspective, Iceland has less than a quarter

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:55.240
[Amit Varma]: of the population of Andheri. And these words were meant as praise for Iceland to put their

00:49:55.240 --> 00:49:59.840
[Amit Varma]: achievement in context. And instead, everybody assumed I was being anti national and dissing

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:04.920
[Amit Varma]: India and I got hugely trolled for it. So not the argumentative Indian, but the abusive

00:50:04.920 --> 00:50:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Indian. But sort of go back to the sort of the public choice question of that and I won't

00:50:09.920 --> 00:50:13.960
[Amit Varma]: ask you to spend much time on this because we discussed it in our episode on urban governance

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:19.920
[Amit Varma]: already. But for listeners who might not have heard that, how can this be mitigated? Like,

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:24.280
[Amit Varma]: obviously, then the solution is clear that you need more power to devolve to local government

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:31.480
[Amit Varma]: so that your local representative actually has the power to do anything, has actually

00:50:31.480 --> 00:50:37.720
[Amit Varma]: the power to do what her constituents desire. But is this ever likely to happen? Because

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:43.240
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that those who have that centralized power are never going to give any of it up.

00:50:43.240 --> 00:50:45.520
[Amit Varma]: How can those incentives change?

00:50:45.520 --> 00:50:50.640
[Guest]: I definitely think one thing that's going to happen is the switch from, you know, right

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:56.960
[Guest]: now, urban issues are not addressed at all. And rural issues are much more on the on the

00:50:56.960 --> 00:51:03.120
[Guest]: table for state legislatures. But that said, this is a rural issue as well. But this is

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:04.120
[Guest]: a universal issue.

00:51:04.120 --> 00:51:10.160
[Guest]: Absolutely. But what I mean is, I do see a switch happening, that state governments will

00:51:10.160 --> 00:51:15.520
[Guest]: recognize urban problems a little bit more than they did before. Now, having said that,

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:21.840
[Guest]: I don't see any incentive for them to devolve power. I think what needs to happen, I think

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:28.280
[Guest]: the impetus has to come from a few great women and men. You know, just so the constitution

00:51:28.280 --> 00:51:33.520
[Guest]: leaves the option open to devolve power, right? It doesn't stop you from doing it, but it

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:39.240
[Guest]: doesn't make it mandatory. So there is the question of, I think we need some good state

00:51:39.240 --> 00:51:45.160
[Guest]: chief ministers who say, you know what, we're going to devolve these four areas to local

00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:48.960
[Guest]: government, and then let's see how it plays out. Because there's nothing constitutionally

00:51:48.960 --> 00:51:56.240
[Guest]: preventing them from doing so. So I do think we need some good show of leadership at the

00:51:56.240 --> 00:52:00.400
[Guest]: state government level. And frankly, we've had a great run with, you know, I mean, we

00:52:00.400 --> 00:52:06.080
[Guest]: have a wide variation in quality of chief ministers. But we've also had good ones, you

00:52:06.080 --> 00:52:10.920
[Guest]: know, not just bad ones. You had states where you actually had better local governance,

00:52:10.920 --> 00:52:16.160
[Guest]: right? Kerala is an example. Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, the southern states are much better on local

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:21.560
[Guest]: governance than the northern states are. So you do have some good examples where obviously

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:27.640
[Guest]: the states either invested in local governance even before the 73rd, 74th amendment, or at

00:52:27.640 --> 00:52:33.360
[Guest]: the very least embraced this idea that you need to devolve power. I think what states

00:52:33.360 --> 00:52:40.540
[Guest]: are not doing is devolving revenue raising authority. I really think one important thing

00:52:40.540 --> 00:52:47.120
[Guest]: to do is bring property taxes under GST. But like you have central and state GST, that

00:52:47.120 --> 00:52:52.520
[Guest]: should be local GST, that should not go to the state. Right? So it's the same system.

00:52:52.520 --> 00:52:57.840
[Guest]: It's just, you know, the same tax rate, but it's who, which is the agency that actually

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:04.200
[Guest]: ends up collecting or getting that revenue. So I think we need to get into a system of

00:53:04.200 --> 00:53:11.400
[Guest]: good property taxes, because property taxes are local. People invest in that local area,

00:53:11.400 --> 00:53:16.160
[Guest]: and property owners will then demand the bank for their buck, and their vote and their tax

00:53:16.160 --> 00:53:20.920
[Guest]: payment will be linked to the same person. Right now, our vote and our tax payment go

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:25.680
[Guest]: to completely different groups. So I really think that is an important step. So, you know,

00:53:25.680 --> 00:53:32.080
[Guest]: maybe the GST could also solve this problem by bringing in property taxes under its fold

00:53:32.080 --> 00:53:36.000
[Guest]: and implementing it at the local government level. Now, you can imagine the biggest opposition

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:40.880
[Guest]: to this is state governments, because they lose potential revenue, and they also lose

00:53:40.880 --> 00:53:48.720
[Guest]: authority. So they are really what is the, you know, the big interest group, which is

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:51.880
[Guest]: blocking this kind of thinking.

00:53:51.880 --> 00:53:56.220
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, you know, I tend to be a little sceptical of this whole notion of

00:53:56.220 --> 00:54:01.480
[Amit Varma]: relying on say benevolent or enlightened chief ministers to make the changes that are necessary

00:54:01.480 --> 00:54:05.520
[Amit Varma]: because the constitution allows them to. But the fact is that the incentives are against

00:54:05.520 --> 00:54:11.360
[Amit Varma]: state and humans react to incentives and something you keep going on and on about and that, you

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:15.680
[Amit Varma]: know, if they just do what the incentives dictate that they will do this will never

00:54:15.680 --> 00:54:16.680
[Amit Varma]: get done. So,

00:54:16.680 --> 00:54:22.760
[Guest]: Fair enough, but you know, I also think that there are multiple incentives in politics,

00:54:22.760 --> 00:54:26.840
[Guest]: right? So of course, there are the incentives of, you know, protecting your turf and getting

00:54:26.840 --> 00:54:32.200
[Guest]: revenue and getting reelected. But I do think a lot of politicians are also interested in

00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:37.000
[Guest]: being remembered. They're interested in, you know, entering the history books. I think

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:40.840
[Guest]: their incentives are much more complex. So I agree with you that there is this whole

00:54:40.840 --> 00:54:45.160
[Guest]: public choice thing, and we can't just rely on people's benevolence. But I'm not saying

00:54:45.160 --> 00:54:52.120
[Guest]: we should rely on their benevolence. I'm just saying they could have multi dimensions to

00:54:52.120 --> 00:54:59.520
[Guest]: how they think they want to be perceived or remembered or reelected. And to that extent,

00:54:59.520 --> 00:55:05.140
[Guest]: for some of them, it might be very much in line with devolving power or experimenting

00:55:05.140 --> 00:55:10.360
[Guest]: with new, you know, new sort of governance ideas and so on.

00:55:10.360 --> 00:55:14.480
[Amit Varma]: And at the local level, even assuming that they were to devolve power, an interesting

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:19.560
[Amit Varma]: point you made earlier when we were chatting about the subject on building a waste management

00:55:19.560 --> 00:55:24.920
[Amit Varma]: system is that while the benefits are diffused, the costs are actually concentrated and a

00:55:24.920 --> 00:55:31.640
[Amit Varma]: few people feel the brunt of it to begin with, which is, again, a reason for opposition against

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:33.440
[Amit Varma]: it. Can you elaborate on that a bit?

00:55:33.440 --> 00:55:39.040
[Guest]: Absolutely. So you know, there is, I mean, even once you resolve the problem and devolve

00:55:39.040 --> 00:55:47.880
[Guest]: power to the local level, there is a current mismatch between the costs and benefits, right?

00:55:47.880 --> 00:55:51.440
[Guest]: So when I go to a store and I buy an apple, I pay the cost for the apple and I get the

00:55:51.440 --> 00:55:56.120
[Guest]: benefits of the apple, right? So the costs and benefits are perfectly aligned. Now, in

00:55:56.120 --> 00:56:01.600
[Guest]: politics, that's not always the case. And it's really not the case in this particular

00:56:01.600 --> 00:56:06.040
[Guest]: instance. So if you need to build a waste management system, it doesn't happen overnight,

00:56:06.040 --> 00:56:10.840
[Guest]: right? So in a place like Andheri, if you had to expand the existing sewage system to

00:56:10.840 --> 00:56:16.720
[Guest]: accommodate the population growth and the migration, you need to dig up all the roads.

00:56:16.720 --> 00:56:21.400
[Guest]: Now, I have been to Andheri and I have driven there in traffic and it's already a nightmare.

00:56:21.400 --> 00:56:26.000
[Guest]: You know, when the metro and things were being built, it was just a nightmare to navigate

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:31.360
[Guest]: the streets of Andheri. So now you have a situation where all the costs are imposed

00:56:31.360 --> 00:56:36.400
[Guest]: in the present, right? All the roads are dug up right now. All the benefits come in the

00:56:36.400 --> 00:56:42.240
[Guest]: future. Babies 10 years from today will have, you know, low levels of infant mortality,

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:46.880
[Guest]: low levels of vulnerability to public health problems. And those babies will work 20 years

00:56:46.880 --> 00:56:53.080
[Guest]: after that, right? 18 years after that. So the benefits are far in the future. The beneficiary,

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:57.400
[Guest]: some of them haven't even been born or are not even in the system yet. All the costs

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:02.580
[Guest]: are upfront today being faced by people who need to get to work fast and things like that.

00:57:02.580 --> 00:57:07.720
[Guest]: So it's obviously a very big problem of, yeah, we would love a sewage system, but we don't

00:57:07.720 --> 00:57:13.280
[Guest]: want our street to be dug up, right? In rural areas, there is also a caste dimension to

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:17.520
[Guest]: the problem. They'll be like, you know, the sewage system can't go behind my house. It

00:57:17.520 --> 00:57:22.480
[Guest]: can't go under my Tulsi plant, right? There are all those dimensions also to think of.

00:57:22.480 --> 00:57:29.840
[Guest]: So there is a lot of opposition to spending the money and the time that needs to be devoted

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:35.280
[Guest]: to building a waste management system because it involves some kind of disturbance of current

00:57:35.280 --> 00:57:40.400
[Guest]: infrastructure. So all the costs are in the present, all the benefits are in the future.

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:45.320
[Guest]: The second problem is all the benefits are dispersed and all the costs are concentrated.

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:49.600
[Guest]: So the benefits are dispersed in the sense that all of us benefit if there is a better

00:57:49.600 --> 00:57:53.940
[Guest]: public waste management system because it leads to better public sanitation and therefore

00:57:53.940 --> 00:58:00.740
[Guest]: better public health, right? All of us benefit if babies are not dying under the age of one.

00:58:00.740 --> 00:58:05.200
[Guest]: So and all of us also benefit if the groundwater is not polluted because we also access it.

00:58:05.200 --> 00:58:14.640
[Guest]: So on and so forth. However, all the costs politically are taken on by the state chief

00:58:14.640 --> 00:58:20.840
[Guest]: minister or the local corporator who are implementing the system right now. Because when everything

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:26.280
[Guest]: is dug up, people will protest, they will vote them out, right? And the benefits will

00:58:26.280 --> 00:58:31.440
[Guest]: be reaped by the municipal corporator or the legislator three terms down. Because that's

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:37.200
[Guest]: when we really saw, oh, I know we suffered through all the dug up roads, but how wonderful

00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:43.280
[Guest]: it is to have a really functional clean environment. So this problem of dispersed benefits and

00:58:43.280 --> 00:58:49.760
[Guest]: concentrated costs and benefits in the future, and costs in the present, this creates a very

00:58:49.760 --> 00:58:56.480
[Guest]: big problem. When we are talking about how do we overcome the interest and actually build

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:01.920
[Amit Varma]: waste management systems. So another way of putting this would be that the benefits are

00:59:01.920 --> 00:59:06.680
[Amit Varma]: unseen and the costs are seen. For example, the guy whose infant daughter could be safe

00:59:06.680 --> 00:59:10.840
[Amit Varma]: from an early death 10 years later, because of a good sewage system today, he can't possibly

00:59:10.840 --> 00:59:15.560
[Amit Varma]: see that now, what he can see is that it's taking him half an hour longer to get to work

00:59:15.560 --> 00:59:20.880
[Amit Varma]: because the roads are dug up and so on and so forth. All the inconveniences are obvious,

00:59:20.880 --> 00:59:26.460
[Amit Varma]: which then leads us to the pessimistic conclusion that even if the structural problems of local

00:59:26.460 --> 00:59:33.680
[Amit Varma]: governance, the sort of the de-linking between votes and money were solved, you would still

00:59:33.680 --> 00:59:36.280
[Amit Varma]: have this problem getting in the way.

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:40.440
[Guest]: No, but you know, it can be I think you still have a better shot at solving it at the local

00:59:40.440 --> 00:59:45.080
[Guest]: level. So right now, if you think about it, we don't have very good charismatic leaders

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:50.840
[Guest]: at the local government level. Why? Because there is not much for them to do. And they

00:59:50.840 --> 00:59:56.440
[Guest]: don't have much revenue raising authority or responsibility. If you actually build a

00:59:56.440 --> 01:00:02.680
[Guest]: sensible structural system, where local governments become important, then you're going to have

01:00:02.680 --> 01:00:07.600
[Guest]: really charismatic people who come in to the local government system and can actually explain

01:00:07.600 --> 01:00:13.920
[Guest]: to the people that, hey, I know it feels like a giant problem today, but there will be a

01:00:13.920 --> 01:00:18.280
[Guest]: benefit from it. I think Prime Minister Modi is fantastic at this. Look at the rhetoric

01:00:18.280 --> 01:00:23.560
[Guest]: he built around demonetization. I don't personally support demonetization. But look at how he

01:00:23.560 --> 01:00:29.500
[Guest]: managed to convince 1.25 billion people that I know it is hugely costly and you're standing

01:00:29.500 --> 01:00:34.440
[Guest]: in line, but this is going to be hugely beneficial to the country and we request you to make

01:00:34.440 --> 01:00:40.740
[Guest]: this sacrifice. And people fell hook, line and sinker. Right. We shouldn't underestimate

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:47.040
[Guest]: the importance of leaders being able to communicate the value of a good project or in the case

01:00:47.040 --> 01:00:52.000
[Guest]: of demonetization, a terrible project. Right. So I really think if we switch the attention

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:58.120
[Guest]: to the local level, you will get people who manage to overcome these problems simply through

01:00:58.120 --> 01:01:04.640
[Guest]: better communication. Have you noticed when there are new buildings being built in Mumbai?

01:01:04.640 --> 01:01:08.520
[Guest]: What happens is they have these huge holdings of how the building will look in the future.

01:01:08.520 --> 01:01:14.160
[Guest]: Right. So all you see is like this awful structure, but you see this beautiful photograph of kids

01:01:14.160 --> 01:01:19.280
[Guest]: playing in a shining swimming pool and all that. You have entrepreneurs who are able

01:01:19.280 --> 01:01:24.560
[Guest]: to project in the future to help you imagine what you can't imagine yourself. Right. And

01:01:24.560 --> 01:01:29.560
[Guest]: I don't see why you can't have that politics. I just don't think anyone has the incentive

01:01:29.560 --> 01:01:34.800
[Guest]: right now to put in that kind of effort and to engage in that kind of entrepreneurship

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:40.320
[Guest]: because nothing is it's not possible to solve anything at the local level. But I do think

01:01:40.320 --> 01:01:46.480
[Guest]: if you had a good structure of local government with good authority, I mean, in New York,

01:01:46.480 --> 01:01:53.560
[Guest]: Bloomberg ran for mayor. Right. Exactly. There was there was an important job there to be

01:01:53.560 --> 01:01:58.040
[Guest]: done, which came with responsibility, which came with power, which came with a certain

01:01:58.040 --> 01:02:04.120
[Guest]: reputation. And he didn't run for the Senate. He ran to be the mayor of New York City. And

01:02:04.120 --> 01:02:09.860
[Guest]: I don't see why that wouldn't happen if you devolved power and authority and revenue raising

01:02:09.860 --> 01:02:15.200
[Guest]: capabilities in India. I do think that can happen. And I think you will see very creative

01:02:15.200 --> 01:02:20.720
[Guest]: political solutions on they won't be uniform, but creative political solutions on how to

01:02:20.720 --> 01:02:25.240
[Amit Varma]: solve these problems. I buy your point, though I disagree with your example. I buy your point

01:02:25.240 --> 01:02:30.320
[Amit Varma]: that if there is a more meaningful role for local government to play, then better leaders

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:35.520
[Amit Varma]: will emerge, especially people who've experienced problems firsthand, like waste management

01:02:35.520 --> 01:02:39.840
[Amit Varma]: or traffic or potholes or whatever, who will then say, hey, I can finally do something

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:44.520
[Amit Varma]: about this because local government has a power. Let me go out there and do something

01:02:44.520 --> 01:02:48.320
[Amit Varma]: and you know, like in the housing society where your parents stay in Noida, people will

01:02:48.320 --> 01:02:53.920
[Amit Varma]: get similarly involved here. So by that point, I don't quite agree with the example of Modi.

01:02:53.920 --> 01:03:00.320
[Amit Varma]: I think this country has suffered too much because he places rhetoric above actual governance.

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:06.400
[Guest]: But I understand the sense in which you think it's a good thing in that case. But what I

01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:15.000
[Guest]: mean is, we do have an example of a political leader who has told people that there is value

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:20.960
[Guest]: in their sacrifice. That's not an easy message to sell, if you really think about it, right,

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:24.640
[Guest]: selling to people that, hey, I know you're waiting four hours in line outside the ATM

01:03:24.640 --> 01:03:30.360
[Guest]: and the bank, but it's all for a great cause. And people did it, right? No rioting. That's

01:03:30.360 --> 01:03:35.160
[Guest]: the part I want to focus on. Not that demonetization was a good idea, or Modi did a great service

01:03:35.160 --> 01:03:40.920
[Guest]: to India by engaging in that kind of rhetoric. But what I mean is, it can be done. And if

01:03:40.920 --> 01:03:46.720
[Guest]: it can be done for a bad idea, I don't see why we can't do it for a good idea, like building

01:03:46.720 --> 01:03:48.120
[Amit Varma]: a waste management system.

01:03:48.120 --> 01:03:51.580
